<h2> Emergence and Development of Debian/PowerPC </h2>

<h3> Linux and PowerPC </h3>
<p>
 Linux for the PowerPC hasn't existed for very long, and has only recently
 been integrated into the Linux "mainstream" (2.2.x kernel). PowerPC support was
 only integrated into the main Linux kernel tree in version 2.2.x. 
 <a href="http://vger.rutgers.edu">Vger</a> was (and still is) the primary
 development source tree for PowerPC Linux.
</p>

<p>
 An anonymous (read-only) CVS repository is available at 
 <a href="http://cvs.on.openprojects.net/">http://cvs.on.openprojects.net/</a>.
</p>

<p>
 This repository can be accessed using the following commands:
</p>

<p>
 <code>$ export
 CVSROOT=':pserver:anonymous@cvs.on.openprojects.net:/cvs/linux'<br>
 $ cvs login<br>
 $ cvs -z3 checkout kernel</code> (or other package)
</p>

<h3> Beginning of the Debian Port </h3>
<p>
 The PowerPC port began in 1997 at the <a href="http://www.linux-kongress.de/">
 German Linux Congress</a> in W&uuml;rzburg. 
 <a href="http://www.infodrom.north.de/Infodrom/tervola.html">A
 PowerPC machine</a> (Motorola StarMax 4000, 200 MHz 604e) was donated to
 the Debian project and it is hosted at the home from Martin "Joey"  Schulze.
</p>

<p>
 This machine is still in use by many Debian developers, and is used to
 create Debian packages for all new source files with the help from an
 <code>Auto-Builder</code> program package.
</p>

<p>
 Additional information about this computer is available from
 <a href="history"> the history page</a>.
</p> 


<h3>Status</h3>
<p>
 Debian/PowerPC is considered to be stable as of February, 1998, and is
 currently being consolidated for release. More than 90% of the Debian
 packages are available, with the remaining packages being processed.
 Debian/PowerPC will be officially released with the next version of Debian
 (2.2; code-named potato).
</p>

<p>
 Highlights will be:
<ol>
 <li> GlibC-2.1.x based
 <li> Linux-2.2.x version
 <li> More then 1700 'free' source packages and more then 3000 binary packages
 <li> All of the other advantages/disadvantages of Debian :-)
</ol>
</p>

<h2>FTP/HTTP Access</h2>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p>
   Packages are available on any complete Debian mirror. Packages are arranged in
   subdirectories, according to the version, stability, and platform.  Thus
   binary packages are available from the 
   <a href="ftp://ftp.debian.org/pub/debian/dists/potato/main/binary-powerpc">/pub/debian/dists/potato/main/binary-powerpc</a>
   directory on any Debian mirror. (The link is to the main Debian site; you
   should probably use a nearby 
   <a href="http://www.debian.org/misc/README.mirrors">mirror site</a>.) <br>
   <br>
   Source packages are available from the same sites, in the directory 
   <a href="ftp://ftp.debian.org/pub/debian/dists/potato/main/source">/pub/debian/dists/potato/main/source</a>.
  </p>
 </li>
 <li>
  <p>
   Using the <a href="http://www.debian.org/distrib/packages">HTTP (Web) interface</a>
   will allow you to view packages by distribution and search for package names and
   strings in package descriptions.
  </p>
 </li>
</ul>

